We are happy to announce that KIPP families will have access to our food pantry every week throughout September 2020. We are now offering families Thursday and Friday pick-up options, varying by site. We will distribute to families on Thursdays at our, Bronx (CPHS and Freedom MS) and Brooklyn sites. On Fridays, families can pick-up food at the Washington Heights and Harlem sites.

„Éª„Éª„Éª
A few weeks ago, Dave Levin sent a letter to all KIPP alumni, and I shared my thoughts with all KIPP staff; both acknowledged the ways in which the school and organizational culture we built and how some of our practices perpetuated white supremacy and anti-Blackness. As we shared then, we need to do more, faster. Over the last few weeks, we have been working to turn these words into action. And while we are taking some immediate steps, there is still much more work to be done to eliminate any practice at KIPP that furthers systemic racism, anti-Blackness and inequities experienced by our students, alumni, families, teachers, and staff. The steps we are sharing today represent a fraction of the conversations we are having about what changes we need to make. We will continue to communicate as additional decisions are made about the actions we will take across the KIPP network. - Richard Barth.

post_text:
#Juneteenth, also known as Jubilee Day or Freedom Day, commemorates June 19, 1865, when Union Gen. Gordon Granger read federal orders in Galveston, Texas, that all previously enslaved people in Texas were free.

Today is a Day of Action for #KIPPNYC.

Some of our schools have planned events or trainings in the pursuit of racial equity and social justice.

Others in our community are participating in our food pantries program, or taking the day to join rallies, attend lectures, or march in protests.

However you decide to take your action, please know that KIPP NYC joins you in actively working to dismantle systems of oppression and marginalization.

post_text:
On Friday, June 19, 2020, KIPP NYC will observe a day of action to honor #Juneteenth and the ongoing fight for Black lives and liberation. All around the country the day will be observed through action and we invite you to do the same. This action can come in many different forms ‚Äì some of your schools have already planned events or trainings in the pursuit of racial equity and social justice. Others of you may decide to participate in our food pantries program which serves KIPP NYC families in three different boroughs. Or you may decide to take action and participate in protests and rallies calling attention to issues around police brutality and state-sponsored violence against Black and Brown people and communities. However you decide to take your action, please know that KIPP NYC joins you in actively working to dismantle systems of oppression and marginalization that are increasingly, and refreshingly, under attack in our country.
#KIPPNYC #BLACKLIVESMATTER

Full statement at https://www.kippnyc.org/news

A message from KIPP NYC‚Äôs President and our Superintendent
We will increase and expand our understanding of systemic racism and oppression. We will examine our organizational practices, as well as dismantle practices that serve to perpetuate racial inequity. We support everyone in our communities partaking in peaceful protest. We encourage volunteering time and resources in support of social justice. Finally, we are deeply committed to becoming an anti-racist organization that will show society how to build a better tomorrow.‚Äù ‚Äì read the full statement at kippnyc.org/news

From @seniorvoice2020 representing @kippnyccollegeprephs
„Éª„Éª„Éª
This is our reality. As black and brown children, this is what we have to face in the world. As a race, we need to come together and make some noise if we want to see change. No more being silent. And for our white teachers: the ones who love us, care about us, and support us, we need you to stand up and get uncomfortable as well! If you truly do care for us, you should feel enraged as well. Your silence is consent for this behavior. Time to make noise!

post_text:
Great to see the innovative Mr. Khuu recognized in Chalkbeat!

"My favorite lesson to teach remotely has been a third-grade class about the three phases of matter and their atomic structure. I had students actually get up and act out how atoms would look in a cell for a solid, liquid and gas. One student, Chloe, demonstrated a solid by holding a yoga pose for 30 seconds, a liquid by showing off her free flowing ballet moves, and a gas by running around throwing her limbs every which way." https://ny.chalkbeat.org/2020/5/8/21252149/turning-laundry-day-into-a-robotics-lab-it-can-be-done-says-this-harlem-teacher

post_text:
KIPP co-founder Dave Levin shares a message to the KIPP NYC community.

‚ÄúOver the past 25 years, KIPP NYC has faced many challenges. During each and every one, our champions and cheerleaders provided beacons of light to guide us through. Twenty-five years ago, when we were forced to host summer school in the Franz Sigel Park on the Grand Concourse because the New York City wouldn‚Äôt provide us a building, a group of donors arranged for breakfast and lunch and a snack every day. After 9/11, another group of supporters made sure that families affected were able to continue paying rent and that health and mental health services were available to all KIPP families. While the pandemic crisis of COVID-19 is the gravest challenge we have ever faced ‚Äì together we will breathe life into three of KIPP NYC‚Äôs core values: Revolutionary Love, Teach Like Harriett, and Find a Way or Make One.‚Äù

Read the full letter here to learn about all we‚Äôre doing, and how you can help.

https://www.kippnyc.org/giving/dave-levin-update-march-2020/

KIPPNYC.ORG

post_text: Check out this essay from Mia, a 7th grader at #KIPPWashingtonHeights!
shared_text:
KIPP Washington Heights Middle School
January 9 at 1:12 PM ¬∑

Happy 2020! We're so proud of 7th grader Mia whose essay on identity, "Dominican-ish", was selected for publication by YES! Magazine! What an honor! Shout-out to Ms. White and Ms. McIntosh for supporting students in submitting their essays through their writing group!

‚ÄúIt‚Äôs difficult being Dominican but born and raised in New York. I‚Äôm supposed to speak fluent Spanish. I‚Äôm supposed to listen to their music 24/7, and I‚Äôm supposed to follow their traditions. I‚Äôm supposed to eat their main foods. I‚Äôm unique and it‚Äôs not only me. Yes, I may not speak Spanish. Yes, I may not listen to their kind of music, but I don‚Äôt think that defines who I am as a Dominican. I don‚Äôt think I should be discriminated for not being the same as most Dominicans. Nobody should be discriminated against for being different from the rest because sometimes different is good.‚Äú

‚ÄîMia Guerrero, KIPP Washington Heights Middle School, New York, N.Y.

Read more students essays from our fall writing contest on identity and honoring ancestral roots.

post_text: We're so grateful to have such terrific leaders and such dedicated speakers who inspire us to get better every day for our kids. Thank you, Derrick Gay.
shared_text:
Derrick Gay is in New York, New York.
November 1, 2019 at 3:11 PM ¬∑ New York, NY ¬∑

I spent my Halloween leading thoughtful and committed KIPP NYC principals and administrators in DEI Strategy. Later, I offered a workshop to staff from across the KIPP NYC Network examining various forms of capital that #KIPPsters and their families bring to school every day. Always appreciate the fellowship and deep learning with my KIPP partners across the country. Looking forward to ongoing work this year!
